04578nam a22005415i 9780822378914DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223789147 a10.1515/97808223789142doi  a(DE-B1597)551858  a(OCoLC)843332846  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.T73bP48 2013 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a070.1/82231 aPeterson, Jennifer Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEducation in the School of Dreams :bTravelogues and Early Nonfiction Film /cJennifer Lynn Peterson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b91 photographs (incl. 10 in color)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Dreamworld of Cinematic Travel -- t1. Varieties of Travel Experience: Burton Holmes and the Travelogue Tradition -- t2. “The Living Panorama of Nature”: Early Nonfiction and the American Film Industry -- t3. “The Five-Cent University”: Educational Films and the Drive to Uplift the Cinema -- t4. “Atop of the World in Motion”: Visualizing the Pleasures of Empire -- t5. Scenic Films and the Cinematic Picturesque -- t6. “A Weird and Affecting Beauty”: Watching Travel Films in the 1910s -- t7. “The Nation’s First Playground”: Wilderness Modernized in the American West -- tEpilogue Reveries of the Solitary Walker -- tNotes -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the earliest years of cinema, travelogues were a staple of variety film programs in commercial motion picture theaters. These short films, also known as "scenics," depicted tourist destinations and exotic landscapes otherwise inaccessible to most viewers. Scenics were so popular that they were briefly touted as the future of film. But despite their pervasiveness during the early twentieth century, travelogues have been overlooked by film historians and critics. In Education in the School of Dreams, Jennifer Lynn Peterson recovers this lost archive. Through innovative readings of travelogues and other nonfiction films exhibited in the United States between 1907 and 1915, she offers fresh insights into the aesthetic and commercial history of early cinema and provides a new perspective on the intersection of American culture, imperialism, and modernity in the nickelodeon era.Peterson describes the travelogue's characteristic form and style and demonstrates how imperialist ideologies were realized and reshaped through the moving image. She argues that although educational films were intended to legitimate filmgoing for middle-class audiences, travelogues were not simply vehicles for elite ideology. As a form of instructive entertainment, these technological moving landscapes were both formulaic and also wondrous and dreamlike. Considering issues of spectatorship and affect, Peterson argues that scenics produced and disrupted viewers' complacency about their own place in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNonfiction filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTravelogues (Motion pictures)zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378914zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822378914/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_D